Bernoulli numbers

{{task|Mathematics}}
<a class="rosetta__link--wiki" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli number" title="wp: Bernoulli number">Bernoulli numbers</a> are used in some series expansions of several functions (trigonometric, hyperbolic, gamma, etc.), and are extremely important in number theory and analysis. 

Note that there are two definitions of Bernoulli numbers; this task will be using the modern usage (as per the National Institute of Standards and Technology convention).

The&nbsp; n<sup>th</sup> &nbsp;Bernoulli number is expressed as&nbsp; <span class="rosetta__text--bold">B</span><sub>n</sub>.
<br>

;Task

:* &nbsp; show the Bernoulli numbers &nbsp; <span class="rosetta__text--bold">B</span><sub>0</sub> &nbsp; through &nbsp; <span class="rosetta__text--bold">B</span><sub>60</sub>.
:* &nbsp; suppress the output of values which are equal to zero. (Other than &nbsp; <span class="rosetta__text--bold">B</span><sub>1</sub>&nbsp;, all <span class="rosetta__text--italic">odd</span>  Bernoulli numbers have a value of zero.)
:* &nbsp; express the Bernoulli numbers as fractions &nbsp;(most are improper fractions).
:* &nbsp; the fractions should be reduced.
:* &nbsp; index each number in some way so that it can be discerned which Bernoulli number is being displayed.
:* &nbsp; align the solidi &nbsp; (<big><b>/</b></big>) &nbsp; if used (extra credit).


;An algorithm
The Akiyama–Tanigawa algorithm for the "second Bernoulli numbers" as taken from <a class="rosetta__link--wiki" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_number#Algorithmic_description" title="wp: Bernoulli_number#Algorithmic_description">wikipedia</a> is as follows:

  <span class="rosetta__text--bold">for</span> <span class="rosetta__text--italic">m</span> <span class="rosetta__text--bold">from</span> 0 <span class="rosetta__text--bold">by</span> 1 <span class="rosetta__text--bold">to</span> <span class="rosetta__text--italic">n</span> <span class="rosetta__text--bold">do</span>
     <span class="rosetta__text--italic">A</span>[<span class="rosetta__text--italic">m</span>] ← 1/(<span class="rosetta__text--italic">m</span>+1)
     <span class="rosetta__text--bold">for</span> <span class="rosetta__text--italic">j</span> <span class="rosetta__text--bold">from</span> <span class="rosetta__text--italic">m</span> <span class="rosetta__text--bold">by</span> -1 <span class="rosetta__text--bold">to</span> 1 <span class="rosetta__text--bold">do</span>
       <span class="rosetta__text--italic">A</span>[<span class="rosetta__text--italic">j</span>-1] ← <span class="rosetta__text--italic">j</span>×(<span class="rosetta__text--italic">A</span>[<span class="rosetta__text--italic">j</span>-1] - <span class="rosetta__text--italic">A</span>[<span class="rosetta__text--italic">j</span>])
   <span class="rosetta__text--bold">return</span> <span class="rosetta__text--italic">A</span>[0] (which is <span class="rosetta__text--italic">B</span><sub><span class="rosetta__text--italic">n</span></sub>)

